name: Command & Conquer
deck: Overall Command & Conquer is a great strategy game and easily the best available on the PlayStation.

name: Return of Arcade
deck: For nostalgia buffs, these old games are worth your time and money, though you will miss the feel of the arcade controller.

name: The Dig
deck: In almost every sense, The Dig represents a leap backwards from LucasArts' previous group of adventure games.

name: Mission Critical
deck: Put simply, Mission Critical was one of the best adventures of 1995.

name: Links LS: Legends in Sports 1997 Edition
deck: With this update, Links LS can rightfully reclaim its status as the king of golf sims.

name: Star Wars Rebel Assault II: The Hidden Empire
deck: Rebel Assault II  will be enough to satisfy those seeking a worthwhile multimedia "experience," but the limited gameplay will send hard-core gamers running back to Tie Fighter.

name: Shannara
deck: Shannara is an excellent pick for novice users or fans of Mr. Brooks, but experienced players should probably keep looking.

name: Screamer (1995)
deck: Screamer shuns the pit stops, personnel moves, and car equipment upgrades that have become familiar to racing fans in favor of colorful, straightforward, hard-driving action.

name: Quake
deck: If you're into action games, or even if you're not, you should be playing Quake right now - it's as good as PC gaming gets.

name: Red Baron II
deck: Red Baron II has a lot to offer, but its rushed shipment makes for a game that's appealing only to those sim fans willing to deal with quirks and inconsistencies while awaiting patches.

name: Earthworm Jim
deck: It's a video game, it's a cartoon, it's a toy, it's a lunch box, and now it's a PC CD-ROM game.

name: Close Combat
deck: A typical day at the beach: the sand under your feet, the roar of the surf... and the ripping sound of German machine guns as they cut your troops to pieces.

name: Outlaws
deck: From the opening level, you'll know you're in for a movie-worthy experience.

name: Diablo
deck: Diablo is the best game to come out in the past year, and you should own a copy. Period.

name: Star Wars: Dark Forces
deck: To its credit, Dark Forces is a good game that doesn't "play itself" like the Rebel Assault games do.

name: Scrabble (1996)
deck: Scrabble was made for computer play.

name: You Don't Know Jack: Sports
deck: I'm pleased to report that they've truly hit the long ball once again.

name: Risk
deck: The best computerized version of Risk yet.

name: Starcraft
deck: It doesn't stray far from the blueprint created by its predecessors, but it is, without a doubt, the best game to ever adhere to that formula.

name: Master of Orion 3
deck: Master of Orion III is a disappointing follow-up to the two most significant space empire games ever.

name: Tomb Raider (1996)
deck: Tomb Raider is simply a smart game, bursting with great touches.

name: The Curse of Monkey Island
deck: Like its predecessors, The Curse of Monkey Island has all the makings of a classic.

name: Interstate '76
deck: Interstate '76 is an incredible gaming experience and offers countless hours of enjoyment for those who are willing to face up to its challenge.

name: NASCAR Racing 2
deck: Allow me to make one crucial point: NASCAR 2 is not a toy.

name: The Elder Scrolls: Chapter II - Daggerfall
deck: Someone has finally returned to the RPGs of the old school and created an adventure that will take even the most experienced gamer months to unravel.

name: Chronicles of the Sword
deck: Chronicles of the Sword takes a classic approach to a classic story—and manages to accomplish very little in the process.

name: Ultimate Yahtzee
deck: Strictly for loners who love the original dice game.

name: Dark Reign: The Future of War
deck: One of the most impressive games released this year in any genre.

name: Rocket Jockey
deck: You won't be disappointed with this novel new title.

name: Leisure Suit Larry: Love for Sail!
deck: Unless you're the proud owner of the Three's Company box set, this game will likely get old quick.

name: Redneck Rampage
deck: Though the tabloid alien-abduction plot feels a bit dated, there's more than enough splatter and gags to compensate.

name: Man of War
deck: The developers were headed in the right direction, but in the end they fail on both fronts.

name: X-COM: Apocalypse
deck: This is almost the X-COM sequel that folks have been hoping for.

name: A-10 Cuba!
deck: Longtime flight-sim fans will take to the realism of A-10 Cuba! like ducks to water, and forgive it its shortcomings.

name: Star Wars Jedi Knight: Dark Forces II
deck: Arguably the best single-player first-person shooter since Doom.

name: Riven: The Sequel to Myst
deck: It's a leisurely paced, all-encompassing, mentally challenging experience. If you enjoyed Myst, you'll thoroughly enjoy Riven.

name: Heavy Gear
deck: With the exception of its lacking originality, Heavy Gear contains all the elements of a successful game and is certainly the finest game of its kind in many months.

name: Warcraft Adventures: Lord of the Clans
Star Wars: Yoda Stories
deck: In Yoda Stories, you assume the role of young Luke Skywalker, Jedi junior varsity and errand boy for Yoda.

name: Unreal
deck: What gives Unreal an edge is how these differences, while not always positive, distinguish it from the legions of other 3D shooters.

name: Hexen II
deck: Hexen II delivers a mighty blow, but ultimately fails to knock the king off his throne.

name: SiN
deck: Sin is for the first-person shooter fan who wants more of the same, done just a little different, but done right.

name: You Don't Know Jack: Movies
deck: In addition to creating a plethora of wacky questions pertaining to film, the producers have also given this version a movie motif.

name: 3D Lemmings
deck: With addictive gameplay, numerous levels, and cute little rodents, 3D Lemmings is a must-buy.

name: Flight Unlimited II
deck: It doesn't have the globe-spanning sweep of Microsoft Flight Simulator, but it renders its own little corner of the world with admirable fidelity.

name: F/A-18 Hornet 3.0
deck: F/A-18 Hornet 3.0 continues the noble tradition of creating a great sim andforgetting to put a game inside of it.

name: Tomb Raider II
deck: Most of Tomb Raider II's improvements are cosmetic.

name: Deathtrap Dungeon
deck: If you didn't care for Tomb Raider's third-person perspective and camera angles then Deathtrap Dungeon will probably leave you cold.

name: Might and Magic VI: The Mandate of Heaven
deck: Might and Magic VI is a classically designed role-playing game that features both a huge gaming world and lots of attention to detail.

name: Croc: Legend of the Gobbos
deck: Croc just didn't live up to its potential.

name: Fighter Squadron: The Screamin' Demons over Europe
deck: Despite the lack of a full campaign, the physics models and top-notch AI make this one of the best dogfighting experiences yet.

name: European Air War
deck: European Air War doesn't push the state of the art, but it excels at good, old-fashioned gameplay.

name: MechCommander
deck: A beautiful-looking strategy game whose design flaws, few as they are, prevent it from achieving its rightful greatness even in spite of its many strengths.

name: Sorry! (1998)
deck: Hasbro Interactive has not only crafted a faithful representation of this ageless board game, but in so doing has included an array of extraordinary features that breathe new life into a time-honored favorite.

name: M1 Tank Platoon II
deck: M1 Tank Platoon II is still an extremely well-done and researched simulation, and is almost worthy of the name.

name: F-22 Air Dominance Fighter
deck: Digital Image Design has crafted the latest and perhaps the most exacting reproduction of the USAF's all-new air supremacy/strike fighter.

name: Boggle CDROM
deck: If you're going to have fun with this game, you've gotta get online.

name: Achtung! Spitfire
deck: Achtung Spitfire is a wargamer's dream.

name: Half-Life
deck: Half-Life is the closest thing to a revolutionary step the genre has ever taken.

name: Wing Commander: Prophecy
deck: The new design team has shifted the emphasis from screenplay to gameplay, and the result is an engaging, but somewhat different, Wing Commander experience.

name: You Don't Know Jack: Television
deck: You Don't Know Jack Television is the popular trivia game with TV themed questions.

name: Total Annihilation
deck: Cavedog has done a commendable job of taking the basic mechanics of real-time strategy and using them to create something new.

name: Close Combat: A Bridge Too Far
deck: Atomic Games has managed to create the ideal sequel: It expands and adds many features while keeping everything that made the first game a joy to play.

name: Quest For Glory V: Dragon Fire
deck: Quest for Glory V has a few quirks and problems that will try your patience, but series fans will want to play this game to see old friends and follow Hero's last adventure.

name: Zork: Grand Inquisitor
deck: Grand Inquisitor is the best graphical Zork yet, and one of the most consistently entertaining adventures of the year.

name: Oddworld: Abe's Oddysee
deck: Abe's Oddysee balances its action and puzzle elements perfectly.

name: Entertainment Pack: The Puzzle Collection
deck: If Microsoft and Pajitnov want to make us forget about Tetris, they're going to have to do a lot better than this.

name: Defiance (1997)
deck: Although this is not a terrible game, there's nothing here that would merit someone to really consider buying it when there are so many other 3D games of such a higher caliber.

name: Microsoft Flight Simulator 98
deck: Microsoft has proven itself fighting fit with a thorough retooling of the classic.

name: 688(I) Hunter/Killer
deck: At last, the long wait for a worthy nuclear submarine simulation is over.

name: WarGames
deck: WarGames is a decent real-time strategy game in the Command & Conquer vein.

name: Lords of Magic
deck: It promised to combine the captivating gameplay of Heroes of Might & Magic II with the style of Lord of the Realm II and an eye-popping graphics engine. Unfortunately, LOM falls far short of its potential.

name: Jetfighter: Full Burn
deck: Mission Studios has essentially taken the Jetfighter III engine and wrapped it all in a cinematic narrative that would have shamed Digital Pictures.

name: Chessmaster 5500
deck: The worst thing you can say about Chessmaster 5500 is that you might not want to spend the bucks on it if you already own Chessmaster 5000.

name: F/A-18 Korea
deck: F/A-18 Korea is an exacting portrayal of the twin-engine F/A-18C/D Hornet dual-purpose fighter.

name: Worms 2
deck: The simple rules and basic control structure make it a game that anyone can learn to play in about five minutes.

name: Frogger (1997)
deck: Frogger is an enjoyable title.

name: Shanghai: Dynasty
deck: Shanghai: Dynasty may be the most ambitious of the computerized translations, integrating a wide array of significant enhancements into an already entertaining system

name: Uprising: Join or Die
deck: Played from a first-person perspective, this frenetic game is unlike anything else in its genre.

name: Grim Fandango
deck: In addition to being a very good adventure game, it features great writing and beautiful art direction.

name: Grand Prix Legends
deck: Grand Prix Legends will reward you with arguably the most intense racing experience ever seen on a personal computer.

name: Sanitarium
deck: Broken into eight chapters, the entire game is a journey through your own madness to potential salvation.

name: Hoyle Casino
deck: If already own a previous game in the series, or you prefer 3D environments and games that test skill rather than chance, you'd be better off taking your bets elsewhere.

name: Scud: Industrial Evolution
deck: The end result is a generic shooter, thinly veiled by its use of an inventive comic series.

name: Ultima IX: Ascension
deck: Ultima IX comes across both as an epic and a farce.

name: X-COM: Interceptor
deck: Because of the lackluster space combat, Interceptor is the first X-COM game where the micromanagement and research portion is the more satisfying of the two halves.

name: Virus: The Game
deck: A botched attempt to meld Descent-like graphics and action with a semblance of real-time strategy, Virus: The Game fails by a wide margin to deliver on its promise.

name: Star Trek: Starfleet Command
deck: Starfleet Command is undoubtedly the best combat-oriented Trek game yet.

name: Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire
deck: Problems with the control, camera angles, and frustrating save feature keep Shadows from reaching its full potential.

name: Commandos: Beyond the Call of Duty
deck: Beyond the Call of Duty ends up feeling like a shadow of its former self, being both shorter and more frustrating than the original.

name: Duke Nukem: Zero Hour
deck: He's all that stands between us and a Time-Spanning Alien invasion. He's Duke Nukem. Gaming's Greatest Action Hero. And this is his finest hour! Zero Hour!

name: Sid Meier's Civilization V
deck: Civilization V features a number of new elements, as well as the addictive gameplay that has made this empire-building series a hit.

name: God of War: Chains of Olympus
deck: Chains of Olympus sees the return of angry demigod Kratos as he hacks and slashes his way through an ultra-violent adventure on the PSP.

name: Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection
deck: Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection features over 40 titles from the SEGA Genesis era.

name: Otherland
deck: Otherland is a massively multiplayer online game based on the best-selling novels by fantasy author Tad Williams.

name: Descent 3
deck: It improves in almost every conceivable way on its predecessors and reestablishes the series as the premier example of the play style it single-handedly pioneered.

name: Quake II Mission Pack: The Reckoning
deck: The question you need to ask yourself is whether you enjoy Quake II enough to merit playing it again, because The Reckoning is a supplement rather than an improvement.

name: USCF Chess
deck: If you don't already know the dos and don'ts of castling etiquette, don't expect to win many games here.

name: Front Page Sports: Trophy Rivers
deck: Occasionally boring, at times just plain annoying, but generally realistic andcomprehensive, Trophy Rivers is surely a game that only a fisherman could love.

name: Virtual Pool 2
deck: Virtual Pool 2 succeeds as being both an entertaining game and an instructional tool.

name: Forsaken (1998)
deck: If you're without a PC or N64, pick up the PlayStation version without fear.

name: The Journeyman Project 3: Legacy of Time
deck: While it looks nice, sounds nice, and plays nice, JP3 is a game hampered by its noticeable lack of story, sloppy writing, and one really annoying "feature."

name: Deer Hunter
deck: The first console Deer Hunter game includes 17 weapons and an online tournament mode.

name: Microsoft Combat Flight Simulator: WWII Europe Series
deck: The strongest element of Combat Flight Simulator is the flight experience itself.

name: Dark Reign Expansion: Rise of the Shadowhand
deck: Rise of the Shadowhand accomplishes the challenging feat of significantly improving one of last year's best and most complex real-time strategy games.

name: Prince of Persia: Arabian Nights
deck: It has two tragic flaws, and these problems are so overwhelming that the good parts seem wasted.

name: Centipede (1999)
deck: While this new Centipede can stand on its own, it fails to capture the magic of the original.

name: Gabriel Knight 3: Blood of the Sacred, Blood of the Damned
deck: It has several problems that will dampen the experience for all but the most die-hard fans of the series.

name: Mastermind (1998)
deck: In the case of Mastermind, Hasbro Interactive may have been better off leaving well enough alone.

name: Triple Play 99
deck: Triple Play 99 is the way to go if you want a realistic baseball sim to play.

name: High Heat Baseball 1999
deck: Underneath High Heat's less-than-spectacular graphics engine lies a very impressive baseball game.

name: Drakan: Order of the Flame
deck: Drakan is clearly one of the better games in its class, even if it doesn't seem especially original.

name: H.E.D.Z. (Head Extreme Destruction Zone)
deck: H.E.D.Z.'s inspired design doesn't always translate into inspiring gameplay, and while it's frequently funny, it's not very fun once the novelty wears off.

name: Leisure Suit Larry's Casino
deck: The combination of the Leisure Suit Larry franchise and a casino game sounds like a match made in sleaze heaven.

name: Dominion: Storm Over Gift 3
deck: Its lack of distinguishing features renders it entirely tedious for real-time veterans, while its difficulty and bland presentation make it the wrong choice for newcomers to the genre.

name: Tribal Rage
deck: Set on yet another postapocalyptic Earth, Tribal Rage lets you battle as one of six allegedly wacky tribes for domination of the scorched planet.

name: Messiah
deck: Messiah is relatively short, and the memorable set pieces are interrupted by too many uninspired jumping puzzles.

name: Revenge of Arcade
deck: Revenge of Arcade's big problem is, surprisingly, the selection of games.

name: Need for Speed III: Hot Pursuit
deck: Need for Speed III is one of the best times I have had playing a racing game.

name: Heart of Darkness
deck: Heart of Darkness is the latest platform/puzzle game from the creators of Out of this World and Flashback.

name: NFL Blitz
deck: Blitz is the most addictive sports game ever created.

name: MechWarrior 3
deck: It might seem rough around the edges once in a while, but nevertheless, MechWarrior 3 is a worthy successor to one of the best games of the decade.

name: Independence War
deck: Independence War not only provides the most detailed flight and systems modeling yet seen in a space sim, it also provides a complex, rewarding plot and a fully fleshed-out gaming world.

name: Urban Assault
deck: There are lots of missions and lots of branches so you can complete several missions in varying order, but all the missions end up playing the same.

name: Commandos: Behind Enemy Lines
deck: A genuinely original game of tactics, planning, and precision.

name: Links LS 1999
deck: Three years of improving this engine has made Links one of the most well-rounded and finely crafted software products on the market.

name: Age of Empires II: The Age of Kings
deck: If you've ever liked any other real-time strategy game in this classical style, then you'll clearly see why this one deserves so much credit.

name: Caesar III
deck: Despite the small problems, building a thriving city in Caesar III is fun.

name: Chessmaster 6000
deck: Chessmaster is still the only way to go if you're looking for a chess program.

name: The Game of Life
deck: The PC conversion of The Game of Life brings some of the charm of the original and tampers very little with the formula.

name: Fallout 2
deck: The core elements of 1997's best role-playing game are intact and, in several ways, have been improved.

name: Jeopardy! (1991)
deck: A version of the popular gameshow is available on the PlayStation.

name: Heroes of Might and Magic III
deck: No doubt a port of the PC version, the Dreamcast version of Heroes of Might and Magic III is bound to deliver the Heroes formula to console strategy fans.

name: Turok 2: Seeds of Evil
deck: It's a landmark shooter and a must-buy.

name: Fly!
deck: Fly has it where it counts: in the cockpit and, for the most part, in the flight model.

name: Wheel of Fortune (1987)
deck: With all the elements that makes Wheel of Fortune so popular on TV, this game will let up to three people play at once.

name: Golf 1999
deck: Now that the Microsoft Golf series is no longer being developed by Access, it's really beginning to shine.

name: Axis & Allies: The Ultimate WWII Strategy Game
deck: The result of all of Hasbro's diligent faithfulness to the source is a great version of a classic board game.

name: Rage of Mages
deck: It isn't particularly original in any specific regard, but its solid combination of features collectively form a unique and enjoyable role-playing game.

name: Hexplore
deck: It's a decent game, but it doesn't represent the state of the art in role-playing games.

name: Lords of Magic: Special Edition
deck: The Special Edition corrects a number of flaws and adds several new features but somehow ends up being only a tiny bit more appealing than its predecessor.

name: Outburst (1998)
deck: This is a case of an interesting party game losing its magic when there's no party around.

name: John Saul's Blackstone Chronicles: An Adventure in Terror
deck: The Blackstone Chronicles isn't a bad game. It's just average to a fault.

name: Smart Games Challenge 3
deck: While Smart Games 3 offers a wide assortment of puzzles, many of them are Mensa-only mind benders.

name: Star Wars: Rogue Squadron 3D
deck: Any fan of the first level of Shadows of the Empire really should check out Rogue Squadron.

name: Tomb Raider III: Adventures of Lara Croft
deck: Those who lost interest in the series with Tomb Raider II may want to give it another look with the third.

name: FIFA 99
deck: While not completely perfect, it's deep on options, packed with real teams and players, and presented with a slick interface.

name: Asteroids
deck: While it might make a better rental than a straight-up purchase, either way you won't go wrong.

name: Thief: The Dark Project
deck: Its emphasis on stealth, strategy, and ingenuity, coupled with its strong narrative structure and excellent mission design, adds up to a game that's stylish, serious, rewarding, and unique.

name: Dark Vengeance
deck: Dark Vengeance isn't a bad game, but it doesn't do anything new and doesn't really provide any compelling reason for playing it.

name: West Front
deck: It's obvious that TalonSoft learned from its mistakes following the release of the disappointing East Front.

name: Deer Hunter II: The Hunt Continues
deck: You can walk around, the horrible map screen has been replaced by a cool GPS device, and the game looks a lot better, albeit not to the quality of most 3D shooters out there.

name: The Elder Scrolls Adventures: Redguard
deck: The excellent story, unique puzzles, and addictive swordplay help make Redguard an immensely rich and enjoyable adventure.

name: Slingo
deck: Unlike chess, checkers, mah-jongg, or any number of two-player classic or board games, there is absolutely no skill involved whatsoever.

name: WWII Fighters
deck: Even with its quirks, this is a standout game - and one that any fan of World War II air combat will want to play.

name: Speed Busters: American Highways
deck: The track design is inventive, the illusion of speed is great, and overall the control is good.

name: Uprising 2: Lead and Destroy
deck: While the changes to Uprising 2 are notable and (for the most part) positive, the game still manages to underwhelm because of some seemingly minor flaws.

name: Gangsters
deck: Gangsters has many interesting features, but they don't come together in the big picture.

name: Baldur's Gate
deck: Baldur's Gate largely manages to meet, and even surpass, gamers' high expectations for this ambitious game.

name: King's Quest: Mask of Eternity
deck: A vast, sprawling experiment that, while falling short of its goal, is enjoyable and noteworthy nonetheless.

name: Star Wars: Force Commander
deck: Because of its dated graphics, ineffective controls, and flawed gameplay, Force Commander falls short of its ambitious intent.

name: Heavy Gear II
deck: Heavy Gear II is the most impressive game yet in the giant robot genre.

name: Starsiege
deck: Starsiege brings new life to a genre otherwise devoid of it, even if it doesn't really succeed in elevating robot sims out of their long-term rut.

name: Battle of Britain (1999)
deck: Like all Grigsby games, Battle of Britain doles out plenty of detail but leaves much room for improvement.

name: Power Chess 98
deck: If Sierra can up the ante in terms of tutorials, game analysis, and openings, the next Power Chess will have the stuff to challenge Chessmaster 5500 for chess supremacy.

name: Stratego (1998)
deck: Stratego occupies a gray area that's more flavorful than backgammon or checkers, but it doesn't have the lasting appeal of those games.

name: Carmageddon 2: Carpocalypse Now
deck: If you're not adverse to a little lowbrow humor and a lot of violence and mayhem, you'll find plenty of action and still more fun in Carmageddon II.

name: Return to Krondor
deck: Return to Krondor may not be an epic sequel to Betrayal at Krondor, but its excellent graphics and immersive plot make it an enjoyable story-driven game.

name: Pro Pilot 99
deck: The good news is that Pro Pilot '99 is a dramatic improvement over that first release, building on the features of that initial release and filling many of the holes.

name: Barrage (1998)
deck: Barrage is heavy on two themes. The first is flying around in a hovercraft. Thesecond is blowing the hell out of anything that even resembles a threat.

name: Motocross Madness (1998)
deck: With its multitude of modes and good terrain graphics, this is pretty much everything you could hope for in a motocross simulation, and then some.

name: Fox Sports Soccer '99
deck: Though not without a handful of control issues and flaws in commentary, the freshness of Fox's approach makes for a great game.

name: Star Wars: X-Wing - Collector Series
deck: These are classic games that belong on every computer gamer's shelf, no doubt about it.

name: Monopoly Star Wars Edition
deck: Though not an entirely bad idea, the actual combination of the two proves to be somewhat pointless.

name: Earthworm Jim 3D
deck: Earthworm Jim 3D has something to discourage all types of people from playing it.

name: Peter Jacobsen's Golden Tee Golf
deck: Golden Tee Golf doesn't contain anything that warrants a recommendation.

name: Indiana Jones and the Infernal Machine
deck: Quirky controls, repetitive puzzles, and a range of other annoying flaws keep this game from being the major-league hit that Indiana Jones fans hoped it would be.

name: Myst (1993)
deck: Embark on an adventure through a mysterious island where clues abound and you must try to reverse a wrong that has gone unchecked for ages.

name: Quake II
deck: Whatever else may be said about Quake II, one thing is certain: It is the only first-person shooter to render the original Quake entirely obsolete.

name: Motorhead
deck: Only the most ardent racing fans need apply.

name: Warzone 2100
deck: Warzone 2100's highly navigable 3D engine, unique campaign structure, and multiplayer gameplay should please most real-time strategy fans.

name: Myth: The Fallen Lords
deck: This fantasy game unfolds around a richly woven plot, involving an epic struggle between the undead and spirit forces of Dark and the living forces of Light.

name: Fox Sports Golf '99
deck: If you're looking for an addictive golfing sim that looks and plays unlike any other, it's definitely worth a look.

name: Battleship (1992)
deck: Not an intensely complicated game with intricate strategic developments to begin with, it's now just a guess-fest.

name: Age of Empires
deck: This is not quite the game you hoped for. Even worse, it has some definite problems.

name: Close Combat III: The Russian Front
deck: Close Combat III: The Russian Front is the best Close Combat game of the bunch.

name: Baseball 2000
deck: Baseball 2000 feels, plays, and looks just the way its name sounds: generic.

name: Test Drive: Off-Road 2
deck: Surprisingly enough, Test Drive Off-Road 2 winds up being a better-playing racing game than Test Drive 5.

name: Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri
deck: Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri is another one of those games that can make hours pass like minutes.

name: Final Fantasy VII
deck: Never before have technology, playability, and narrative combined as well as in Final Fantasy VII.

name: Heretic II
deck: You wouldn't want to live there, but the world of Heretic II is a beautiful place to visit.

name: Requiem: Avenging Angel
deck: The pacing and story aren't as good as Half-Life's, but the character interaction and angelic powers elevate the game beyond many other shooters.

name: Gruntz
deck: A puzzle game that falls somewhere between Pyro Studios' Commandos and Psygnosis' Lemmings Paintball.

name: Civilization: Call to Power
deck: Whatever else you may think about Call to Power, you have to admire the ambition behind the effort.
